{"parse":{"title":"Joseph Salim Peress","pageid":5314068,"revid":857708384,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux\" style=\"display:none\">Pioneering British diving engineer, inventor of some of the first truly usable atmospheric diving suits </div>\n<table class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\"><span class=\"fn\">Joseph Salim Peress</span></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Born</th><td>\n1896</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Died</th><td>\nJune 4, 1978</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Occupation</th><td class=\"role\">\nEngineer</td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<b>Engineering career</b></td></tr><tr class=\"note\"><th scope=\"row\">Significant design</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Atmospheric_diving_suit\" title=\"Atmospheric diving suit\">Atmospheric diving suit</a></td></tr><tr style=\"display:none\"><td colspan=\"2\">\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:302px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tritonia_Lusitania_1935.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Tritonia_Lusitania_1935.jpg/300px-Tritonia_Lusitania_1935.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"197\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Tritonia_Lusitania_1935.jpg/450px-Tritonia_Lusitania_1935.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Tritonia_Lusitania_1935.jpg/600px-Tritonia_Lusitania_1935.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1828\" data-file-height=\"1200\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tritonia_Lusitania_1935.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Two divers, one wearing the \"Tritonia\" ADS and the other standard diving dress, preparing to explore the wreck of the <a href=\"/wiki/RMS_Lusitania\" title=\"RMS Lusitania\">RMS Lusitania</a>, 1935.</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Joseph Salim Peress</b> (1896 &#8211; June 4, 1978), was a pioneering British diving engineer, inventor of one of the first truly usable <a href=\"/wiki/Atmospheric_diving_suit\" title=\"Atmospheric diving suit\">atmospheric diving suits</a>, the <i>Tritonia</i>, and was involved in the construction of the famous <a href=\"/wiki/JIM_suit\" title=\"JIM suit\">JIM suit</a>.\n</p><p>Salim Peress grew up in the Middle East. It is said that his interest in diving suit design started from the observations of the <a href=\"/wiki/Persian_Gulf\" title=\"Persian Gulf\">Persian Gulf</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Pearl_divers\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pearl divers\">pearl divers</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-scribe71_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-scribe71-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Peress had a natural talent for engineering design, and had challenged himself to construct an articulated atmospheric diving suit (ADS) that would keep divers dry and at atmospheric pressure, even at great depth. At the time, little was known about <a href=\"/wiki/Decompression_stop\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Decompression stop\">decompression</a> diving. Various atmospheric suits had been developed during the <a href=\"/wiki/Victorian_era\" title=\"Victorian era\">Victorian era</a>, but nobody had yet managed to overcome the basic design problem of constructing a joint which would remain flexible and watertight at depth without seizing up under pressure.\n</p><p>In 1918 Peress began working for WG Tarrant at <a href=\"/wiki/Byfleet\" title=\"Byfleet\">Byfleet</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/United_Kingdom\" title=\"United Kingdom\">United Kingdom</a>, where he was given the space and tools to develop his ideas about constructing an ADS. His first attempt was an immensely complex prototype machined from solid <a href=\"/wiki/Stainless_steel\" title=\"Stainless steel\">stainless steel</a>.\n</p><p>In 1923 Peress was asked to design a suit for salvage work on the wreck of the <a href=\"/wiki/Peninsular_and_Oriental_Steam_Navigation_Company\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company\">P&amp;O</a> liner <a href=\"/wiki/SS_Egypt\" title=\"SS Egypt\">SS <i>Egypt</i></a> which had sunk in 122&#160;m (400&#160;ft) of water off <a href=\"/wiki/Ushant\" title=\"Ushant\">Ushant</a>. He declined, on the grounds that his prototype suit was too heavy for a diver to handle easily, but was encouraged by the request to begin work on a new suit using lighter materials. By 1929 he believed he had solved the weight problem, by using cast magnesium instead of steel, and had also managed to improve the design of the suit's joints by using a trapped cushion of oil to keep the surfaces moving smoothly.\n<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\nThe oil, which was virtually non-compressible and readily displaceable, allowed the limb joints to move freely at depths of 600&#160;ft (180&#160;m), where the pressure was 520&#160;psi (35&#160;atm). Peress claimed that the Tritonia suit's joints could function at 1,200&#160;ft (370&#160;m) although this was never proven.\n</p><p>In 1930 Peress revealed the Tritonia suit. By May it had completed trials and was publicly demonstrated in a tank at <a href=\"/wiki/Byfleet\" title=\"Byfleet\">Byfleet</a>. In September Peress' assistant <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Jim_Jarret&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Jim Jarret (page does not exist)\">Jim Jarret</a> dived in the suit to a depth of 123&#160;m (404&#160;ft) in <a href=\"/wiki/Loch_Ness\" title=\"Loch Ness\">Loch Ness</a>. The suit performed perfectly, the joints proving resistant to pressure and moving freely even at depth.\n</p><p>The suit was offered to the <a href=\"/wiki/Royal_Navy\" title=\"Royal Navy\">Royal Navy</a> which turned it down, stating that Navy divers never needed to descend below 90&#160;m (300&#160;ft).\n</p><p>Jim Jarret made a deep dive to 90&#160;m (300&#160;ft) on the wreck of the <a href=\"/wiki/RMS_Lusitania\" title=\"RMS Lusitania\">RMS Lusitania</a> off south Ireland, followed by a shallower dive to 60 metres (200&#160;ft) in the <a href=\"/wiki/English_Channel\" title=\"English Channel\">English Channel</a> in 1937 after which, due to lack of interest, the Tritonia suit was retired. Peress abandoned work on diving suits and instead turned to pioneering work in plastic moulding, later forming a company which became the world's largest manufacturer of <a href=\"/wiki/Gas_turbine\" title=\"Gas turbine\">gas turbine</a> blades for the aircraft industry.<sup id=\"cite_ref-scribe71_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-scribe71-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 1965,<sup id=\"cite_ref-scribe71_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-scribe71-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Peress came back from retirement, starting his collaboration with two British engineers, Mike Humphrey and Mike Borrow, interested in designing a modern atmospheric diving suit. The first order of business was finding the original Tritonia suit, which turned up in a <a href=\"/wiki/Glasgow\" title=\"Glasgow\">Glasgow</a> warehouse.<sup id=\"cite_ref-loftas1973_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-loftas1973-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> After all these years, the old suit was still in working conditions, and the octogenarian Peress became the first person to test it in a factory test tank.<sup id=\"cite_ref-scribe71_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-scribe71-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In 1969 Peress became a consultant to UMEL (Underwater Marine Equipment Limited), the new company formed by Humphrey and Borrow, \nwhich eventually created the JIM suit, which was named after Peress' diver Jim Jarret.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes_and_references\">Notes and references</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Joseph_Salim_Peress&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Notes and references\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-scribe71-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-scribe71_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-scribe71_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-scribe71_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-scribe71_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite id=\"CITEREFTaylor1997\" class=\"citation\">Taylor, Colin (October 1997), <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20141226160540/http://www.divernetxtra.com/history/jim1097.htm\">\"Jim, but not as we know it\"</a>, <i>Diver</i>, archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.divernetxtra.com/history/jim1097.htm\">the original</a> on 2014-12-26</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Diver&amp;rft.atitle=Jim%2C+but+not+as+we+know+it&amp;rft.date=1997-10&amp;rft.aulast=Taylor&amp;rft.aufirst=Colin&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.divernetxtra.com%2Fhistory%2Fjim1097.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJoseph+Salim+Peress\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span>, reprinted, slightly abbreviated as:\n<cite class=\"citation\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.dangoor.com/71page24.html\">\"The Joseph Peress Diving Suit\"</a>, <i>The Scribe, Journal of Babylonian Jewry</i> (71): 24, April 1999</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Scribe%2C+Journal+of+Babylonian+Jewry&amp;rft.atitle=The+Joseph+Peress+Diving+Suit&amp;rft.issue=71&amp;rft.pages=24&amp;rft.date=1999-04&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.dangoor.com%2F71page24.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJoseph+Salim+Peress\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span>. The entire issue is also available <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.thescribe.info/pdf/TheScribe71.pdf\">as PDF</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16735067\">Remarkable diving suit</a>, SMH, 1930-12-02</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Patent no. 1,402,645, \"Flexible joint for diving dresses\", applied for April 30, 1921. In:\n<cite class=\"citation\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=IOJ1ZiHvtq8C&amp;pg=PA143\"><i>Official Gazette of the United States Patent Office</i></a>, <b>294</b>, United States. Patent Office, January 1922, p.&#160;143</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Official+Gazette+of+the+United+States+Patent+Office&amp;rft.pages=143&amp;rft.pub=United+States.+Patent+Office&amp;rft.date=1922-01&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DIOJ1ZiHvtq8C%26pg%3DPA143&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJoseph+Salim+Peress\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-loftas1973-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-loftas1973_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite id=\"CITEREFLoftas1973\" class=\"citation\">Loftas, Tony (1973-06-07), <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=gnI8IGtKy64C&amp;pg=PA621\">\"JIM: homo aquatico-metallicum\"</a>, <i>New Scientist</i>, <b>58</b> (849): 621\u2013623, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number\" title=\"International Standard Serial Number\">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/issn/0262-4079\">0262-4079</a></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=New+Scientist&amp;rft.atitle=JIM%3A+homo+aquatico-metallicum&amp;rft.volume=58&amp;rft.issue=849&amp;rft.pages=621-623&amp;rft.date=1973-06-07&amp;rft.issn=0262-4079&amp;rft.aulast=Loftas&amp;rft.aufirst=Tony&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DgnI8IGtKy64C%26pg%3DPA621&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJoseph+Salim+Peress\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Joseph_Salim_Peress&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.divingheritage.com/atmospherickern.htm\">http://www.divingheritage.com/atmospherickern.htm</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.dangoor.com/71page24.html\">http://www.dangoor.com/71page24.html</a></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1231\nCached time: 20180902140534\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.240 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.291 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 1481/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPos